segments.text: One, two, three, four, testing.
Murray, now you say something.
Hello, hello, I'm here.
This is September the 12th, and I have the pleasure and honor of chatting with the postdoctoral role
while I join the faculty at Cornell.
Dr. Morris Bloodworth, who was head of the department at Texas A&M during those years
and who had served on my master's committee,
had told me at many professional meetings that it was just a matter of time
until he would recruit me back to Texas A&M for faculty.
So after I'd been at Cornell five years, Dr. Bloodworth came along with a faculty offer.
By that time, I'd developed quite a good feel for Cornell.
Really was uncertain about whether I would be granted tenure there or not
and knew if I was not going to receive tenure, the decision would be a very easy one.
But if I actually served on the Cornell faculty as an associate professor for two months,
I'd have to go back to Texas A&M.
That was probably the hardest professional decision I've ever made.
You can look back even to this day and wonder, I guess, in some respects,
whether it was the right decision or not.
A lot of things played into it.
We were about 1,800 miles from my family,
and we were 1,000 miles from my wife's family,
and they were 1,000 miles apart.
And that made any kind of, well, it took all the vacation.
We had in the summer in those days with young children to,
we'd spend three weeks vacation and we'd spend about half of it on the road.
And so that was a strong motivating factor.
I did not know whether my wife, who was a native of Wisconsin,
whom I met during my Ph.D. years,
more familiar with the soil than the state,
and to interact with Dr. Dixon, who preceded me here by about two months.
So we had the same kind...
We had the same kinds of research interests.
Well, it really...
And then Chambers County, I remember down on the Gulf Coast,
and those were all one-week stays and seen very extensively.
Those would come during what we call a final field review
for the survey of those counties, the soil survey.
So you go to all the parts of the county and you see the major kinds of soils
that occur in that environment and discuss all of the different controversies
about how to classify them.
And their uses and limitations and that kind of thing.
That was an extremely fortunate to have that luxury and time,
I suppose you'd say, in the first year.
But to this day, I use a lot of slides in teaching the introductory soils course
that I got in that first nine months I was here.
And not to mention just the knowledge and appreciation
for the variety of soils in the state.
What else did you learn
about the people of Texas and their variety from those weeks?
Well, I don't know if...
Of course, I grew up in Texas, and since I went to A&M,
I guess you could say I'd had classmates from all parts of the state.
One of the things when I first began teaching that truly shocked me
was the variety in terms of origin of surnames
of students I had in class in Texas as compared to New York State.
If you'd asked me offhand,
I would have said there would have been a lot greater cultural diversity
in the student body at Cornell University than there would be at Texas A&M.
That's not the case.
There's a much...
I immediately encountered so many different...
From all over Eastern Europe and Germany and those...
Not to mention the Hispanic influence here as compared to New York.
So, about the only thing you could say...
At Cornell, in contrast, would be a much greater Jewish presence
among the students at Cornell than here.
I didn't recognize at that time,
I wouldn't have recognized a Jewish surname from any other name,
but I had a lab technician who was quite good at it
and had some prejudices,
so he didn't hesitate to express his feelings about some.
Incidentally, the Jewish students at Cornell were outstanding students,
in the classroom, the exceptional students.
Describe your getting settled into the department.
Where was it, about how many people,
who were the key leaders of the department in 1968?
That became head in 1963 and continued in that role until 1979,
so he was obviously the kingpin in the department at that time.
Actually, the department probably had more graduate students
at that time than it has today.
The faculty was not as large, although it...
Dr. Bloodworth hired his first faculty member, I believe, in 1964, or five.
And in 1968, counting faculty here and off campus,
I believe there were five or six employees in that year alone.
And then continuing through the mid-'70s,
there was...
There was a considerable addition to the faculty
in terms of breadth of expertise in soil science as well as other disciplines.
So that was a period, well, a period for the entire university,
but it was a period of very rapid growth for the department.
And I think that was primarily his leadership.
I think almost anybody, even today, here,
would tell you that Morris Bloodworth and, as I mentioned, O.D.
and maybe Perry,
they've got the lion's share
of the increases that were enjoyed during those early years.
Was George Kunze, he had already moved to the graduate college when I got here.
Jack Ruckles was soon to become director of Water Resources Institute.
So Jack would have been a leader, but, gosh, there were a number of other faculty members.
About how many total?
On campus, probably, this is a wild guess.
I don't, I don't know, probably 30, I'm guessing, 30.
What do you think the national reputation of the department was then?
Not very good.
I think you can generally say that for most.
But by that time, by that time, recognized as an up-and-coming place.
Because we'd already, by that time, just beginning to see, really, the takeoff that stemmed from all those decisions
that Dr. Rutter was instrumental in making and bringing to fruition.
So the enrollment was definitely on the upswing, beginning to hire faculty,
having a lot of retirements of some people who had done, had performed yeoman service,
but of an entirely different type than faculty to give you any kind of national presence would give.
Where were you all located and what were your facilities?
Well, the department's always been in several buildings.
As large a facility as we have now, you'd think we'd all be in one building, but we aren't.
At that time, I was housed in the, what is now the Butler Building.
It was known then as the Grumman Building.
And the building next to it, we referred to as the old Red Brick Building,
and most of the soils faculty were in that building, but I was never housed in that building.
That's over near the system?
Yeah, the Butler Building is the,
is kind of across from the old Physics Building and the Trigon, the military science building.
The one with the big columns in front, you look down at the MSD area,
you look right into the Grumman Building, and the old Red Brick Building is no longer red,
but it still stands, was immediately next to that one on the northwest side,
so it would be in a sense further up the street toward the Cushing Library at that time.
So we, we occupied primarily those two buildings.
Shared the, the State Chemist at that time was in the old Red Brick Building.
In fact, it was called the State Chemist Building, but a lot of the soils faculty were in there.
It was a, it was a dungeon.
No air conditioning, no central air in any of those buildings at that time.
All window air conditioning.
Where were the labs that you, you and other, and your colleagues used for your instruction?
Well, the lab that I used was on the first, in the,
kind of basement, half basement in the old agronomy building.
I mean, it had windows, but it was mostly below ground, half and half.
The, the man who had been teaching in that position had,
well, it really wasn't his first love.
He'd taught a senior level course before teaching that.
He was known for being reasonably cantankerous.
And then there was a, a fellow that preceded him whose nickname was
Whiskey Jack.
Guys used to talk about finding him inebriated on lab benches at times.
I would say that, that basic soils course, which is very important in the entire agricultural activity,
it needed, it needed some attention.
And the lab was, oh, it was in pitiful shape.
And, and my predecessor was in it through the fall and spring of 1968, 69, and my first teaching at
Texas A&M was in the summer of 1969.
So I had, I couldn't, I didn't have any access to the facility until he was gone.
I think it's fair to say I've never worked harder in my life than I worked that summer.
As, as you, during that first year, what kind of advice did anyone give you about being a faculty member here or anything like that?
Did anybody give you any guidelines or rules or?
No, I, you know, I don't remember being given a lot of advice.
I, I guess I probably got as much advice, advice from Dean Kunkle as anybody, although I didn't spend a lot of time with Dean Kunkle.
But, but he was always philosophized with you a little bit.
Dr. Potts, of course, was an institution at that time in the College of Agriculture, his associate dean, and I'll have to give, I'll have to give him a lot of credit in this sense.
But Dr. Potts was with Kunkle for those first two or three years, he encouraged me to go to regional teaching workshops and anything that, that came up that, that I think he thought
would be any kind of help or guidance in teaching, he was, he was very eager to encourage you to take part in it.
Dr. Bloodworth would always support him, but he would never think about having somebody.
Yeah.
for those kinds of opportunities, Dr. Potts did.
And so he had a major role in getting me out
to learn about developments in the technological aspect
of the teaching at that time.
And it was extremely supportive.
Within the department, actually the man I followed
had been the graduate advisor for the department.
And in addition to teaching the undergraduate course,
I almost inherited that role.
And that meant almost from day one,
while I didn't have graduate students myself,
other than some, well, I did have a few,
but very few along.
But basically, I interacted with all of the faculty
in that role as graduate advisor.
So I had a lot of opportunity to interact
with other faculty members across a pretty,
I mean, our department, I mean,
our department represents a wide variety of disciplines.
So I had an opportunity to interact with a lot of people
that I wouldn't have otherwise.
What was it, now you were a former student
from this department, did that turn out to be an advantage,
a disadvantage, or a mixed blessing
as you were a young, new faculty member?
It was obviously an advantage
in getting a job in the first place.
But none of it, I don't think it had anything to do with it.
None of the veterans came in to talk down to you or anything?
No, no, I know, no, I know.
A lot of them, so many of us were at the same time.
What did you and your colleagues think were the unspoken,
unwritten guidelines about when you went to work,
what you wore, how you did your job?
What did you assume were the guidelines
for you as a professional?
Well, I expect, I expect most of us,
thought we ought to be at work at eight o'clock
in the morning, we ought to stay there till five,
and obviously all of us were 12-month employees,
so we felt unless it was a holiday
or we were on vacation, we should be there.
And how did you?
Now, address was, I think most of us
always wore a tie when we were going to the classroom.
But a lot of the work of faculty in the department's
always been field-oriented, so I think it's always been
reasonable if you were not in the classroom to dress casually.
And you're, beginning in 69, what were your,
what were your responsibilities for courses and so forth
in the early years?
What courses were you to teach and?
Oh, well, you know, this is, but pretty much throughout
my entire career, my major responsibility in teaching
has been one course.
It's been the introduction.
Oh.
It's been the introductory course in soil science.
What number?
Agronomy 301.
Did it have a nickname among the students?
Well, I've heard it referred to as
Murray Milford's Magical Mystery Hour at times, too.
Okay, okay.
And what's the?
Some of the students went out one year
and bought t-shirts and came back in with them on,
had Milford's clods on the back of their t-shirts.
And this is normally to juniors?
It's a junior level course.
Okay.
But it's taken by anything from sophomores to graduate students.
And probably most of those, most of the years I've taught it,
it's been maybe more juniors than anything else,
but next to that, seniors.
And it almost ranged all the way from, I guess,
when I first started, around 100 students a semester.
We've always taught it fall, spring, and summer.
I have not, I have not missed since, you know,
since, well, since the summer of 69,
I've not missed a summer, fall, or spring to teach that course.
Now, when enrollment, the enrollment went as high as 426.
And I had them all that semester.
Shortly thereafter, we were able to add some faculty.
So there have been a couple of other people who have taught the course.
And this is the basic course for
anyone majoring in soil and crop sciences, and what else?
It's been a required course.
It's, of course, it's required for all the students that are major.
But it's been a required course in many other disciplines over the years.
Not as many today as in the past.
But when I came here, it was required for all students in animal science,
recreation, parks, horticulture, agricultural education,
rangeland ecology, management, would have been rangeland science back then.
Plant science is strongly recommended in a couple of areas in ag economics,
wildlife and fisheries required in part of their programs.
Always had some students from geology, some study in earth science for teaching purposes.
No, no engineers, no M.E.s, or?
No agricultural engineering.
It was required in ag engineering, but not, no, none of that.
What were, as you started out in that course, what were your private guidelines for how
you were hoping to do the course?
What, for you as a teacher, what was your philosophy?
I really don't know all the things that shaped how I put the course together.
I suppose you could say I was strongly influenced by what I found at Cornell when I began teaching
there.
The textbook used for the course there was, at that time, called Buckman and Brady.
It goes back into, the textbook is now in its 12th edition, I believe.
It goes back into the 1920s, probably.
And Dr. Brady was the department head, actually.
He moved to the department head when I became a member of the faculty.
But there, we alternated teaching that course there.
One fella taught it in the fall, I taught it in the spring, and then we alternated in
the summer to teach it.
And this fella had more experience with that course than I did, but we met together every
summer and went over the content of the laboratory and has a laboratory with it.
So we, in effect, re-did the laboratory exercises every summer.
And so I had a chance to make inputs into those.
So I guess the content was pretty much the same.
I think it was a little different.
I think it was a little different.
I think it was a little different.
I don't know the exact shape of that, although the fella that I took introductory
soils from at Texas A&M was a man named Hank Foth.
F-O-T-H?
F-O-T-H.
He was only at Texas A&M three years when he went to Michigan State, which I believe
was his alma mater, and he spent the rest of his career there.
He gave, I thought he was an excellent teacher and subsequently I think Michigan State proved
that.
wrote a textbook as well.
His textbook I got a lot of ideas from, but it was not
nearly as, oh meaty is probably the right term, as the one that we had at
Cornell.
So I used, I used, but I took ideas from it.
And that's how we, we
developed the course.
And I would say it is not, it's not as far as the
organization and topics treated.
It's not changed substantially over the years.
With the big emphasis on behavioral objectives or instructional objectives
that was beginning to be a big deal in the late 60s and early 70s.
I totally did
instructional objectives, which I had not done before.
Somewhere early on, and I, do you
know right now, I'm not at all sure whether I started doing it at Cornell or
not, but I think maybe I did.
Remember, I was on the faculty there from 1963 to 1968.
It was during a period,
Vietnam, during a period where I think faculty became very hesitant to say
anything controversial to students.
You weren't supposed to.
I, I'm not, and I'm
not, honestly not sure when I started doing it, but I started early on to think
that in addition to trying to teach subject matter, cognitive and subject matter,
the faculty member had about as much responsibility to try to be a witness to
life, philosophize a little bit about life, and what it is all about.
So, I would
always editorialize.
And when I started doing this, I'm not sure, but I did it at
Cornell.
I know the idea for doing it was developed there, and I think I probably did.
But, so I always tell my
classes, first five minutes are mine.
We talk about whatever we want to.
You know,
this semester, I've already done it. I've done it. I've done it. I've done it. I've done it. I've done it. I've done it. I've done it. I've done it. I've
already talked about bonfire.
I've talked about credit cards and their use.
Talked about alcohol.
Talked about
silver taps being an important tradition.
Urging to participate.
Talked about being
environmentally aware.
Take trash out of the classroom.
Close doors behind you when you go in and out of the classroom.
So, I've done that kind of thing.
All of it.
Yeah.
And I have a final editorial that runs about 25 minutes, which is, that's the only time that I make any overt statement about being a Christian, but I do.
In that final 25 minutes of class.
And what's been the reaction, you think, over the years?
More favorable comments about the editorials on the Course Critique Questionnaire and anything else.
We'll get somewhere between two and five comments in the vein of, I'll pay my money to take
soil science, I don't care to hear your philosophy.
I've never been bothered by those, because I feel like at least once a
trust, I've picked them in a pretty sensitive spot.
In all of your teaching, did you have any role models that affected the way you did it?
Probably my mother and dad.
Bigger role models than anybody.
I come from a family of three.
Mm-hmm.
I come from a family of teachers.
Mm-hmm.
My mother was a teacher.
Her sisters were teachers.
Her brother was a teacher.
So, there were four of them.
They were all teachers.
